04169nam a22005895i 9780231539913DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2014043951  a(OCoLC)984630177  a97802315399137 a10.7312/beli173162doi  a(DE-B1597)458246  a(OCoLC)919252258  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBL2532.S3bB45 2015 4aBL2532.S3bB45 2015 7aREL0290002bisacsh04a299.6/742231 aBeliso-De Jesús, Aisha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aElectric Santería :bRacial and Sexual Assemblages of Transnational Religion /cAisha Beliso-De Jesús.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGender, Theory, and Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAuthor’s Note -- tPreface. Despedidas -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION. Transnational Santería Assemblages -- t1. Electric Oricha -- t2. Transnational Caminos -- t3. Pacts with Darkness -- t4. Scent of Empire -- t5. Contaminating Femininities -- tEPILOGUE. A Death at Dawn -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSantería is an African-inspired, Cuban diaspora religion long stigmatized as witchcraft and often dismissed as superstition, yet its spirit- and possession-based practices are rapidly winning adherents across the world. Aisha M. Beliso-De Jesús introduces the term "copresence" to capture the current transnational experience of Santería, in which racialized and gendered spirits, deities, priests, and religious travelers remake local, national, and political boundaries and reconfigure notions of technology and transnationalism.Drawing on eight years of ethnographic research in Havana and Matanzas, Cuba, and in New York City, Miami, Los Angeles, and the San Francisco Bay area, Beliso-De Jesús traces the phenomenon of copresence in the lives of Santería practitioners, mapping its emergence in transnational places and historical moments and its ritual negotiation of race, imperialism, gender, sexuality, and religious travel. Santería's spirits, deities, and practitioners allow digital technologies to be used in new ways, inciting unique encounters through video and other media. Doing away with traditional perceptions of Santería as a static, localized practice or as part of a mythologized "past," this book emphasizes the religion's dynamic circulations and calls for nontranscendental understandings of religious transnationalisms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aSanteriazCuba. 0aSanteriazUnited States. 7aRELIGION / Ethnic & Tribal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070982708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066586440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/beli1731640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231539913423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231539913/original  a978-3-11-066586-4  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070982-7  CUP Single-User eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles